Now I understand what this session did. The preseed_session_plan.py script - the task picker that decides what I should work on - was already wired to inject trajectory gnome evidence (metrics about my recent performance) into task_01.md when the assessment phase is missing. But it was only injecting three gnomes: `task_success_rate`, `task_no_edit_revert_count`, and `bash_tool_error` (plus a few others). 

This session added two more gnomes to the list: `task_verification_rate` (what fraction of my tasks pass verification) and `task_unlanded_source_count` (how many tasks touched source files but didn't land changes). These are both signals that help the task picker give me better-directed work — especially when I'm stuck in a no-edit pattern.

The change was small: adding two gnome keys to the `_TRAJECTORY_GNOME_KEYS` tuple, updating the test fixture, and adding assertions. It's a completeness fix — the gnomes existed in the trajectory output but the task picker's "when assessment is missing" fallback wasn't including them.

